<subSubSection id="D92C5C8A38C229041FA4A08A8FCCA6BC" pageId="0" pageNumber="19" type="description">
<paragraph id="D1EA1C1778A05AFEB3C807108F604931" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0F34940EFE58BA62A609C0BBEFA627D7" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">
Perennial herbs, 12-30 cm tall. Stolons absent. Rhizomes rather short. Leaves all basal; petiole 5-12 cm long, crisped villous dark-purple (ca. 6 mm); leaf blade reniform, thick leathery, 2.5-4.0 cm long 
<normalizedToken id="8F41BD12131065B99E4ADD078B0F66E0" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
3.5-5.3 cm wide, base cordate, margin undulate, apex obtuse, both surfaces crisped villous dark-purple (5.0-9.0 mm long), adaxially greenish, abaxially purple or dark red, with white spots. Inflorescence paniculate, ca. 20 cm long. 5-10-flowered; branches 2.0-3.0 cm long, glandular pubescent, 1-2-flowered; pedicels slender, 1.0-2.0 cm long, glandular pubescent. Flowers zygomorphic; sepals 5, spreading to reflexed, narrowly ovate, 2.5-3.5 mm long 
<normalizedToken id="C9145BB98CFA1017C30EE6D38D157C7F" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1.5-2 mm wide, glabrous, abaxially red, with white verruculose, adaxially greenish, 3-5-veined, apex obtuse. Petals 5, greenish, margin entire, glabrous, apex acute; the three smallest lanceolate, 3.0-4.0 mm long 
<normalizedToken id="429F0C16C02BDF346EAEF0E717F90206" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1.0-1.2 mm wide, 3-veined; the two largest lanceolate oblong, 0.7-1.4 cm long 
<normalizedToken id="7E9F68E467FDBBD152BE709610C82B84" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1.0-1.2 mm wide, 3-veined. Stamens 10, 3.2-4.0 mm long. Ovary ovoid, 1.5-2.0 mm long, disc obscure; styles divergent ca. 1.0-1.8 mm long. Capsule beaks winged when mature, carpels 5-7 mm long 
<normalizedToken id="599B5D34A2E8D65A84BBEEAC2014C891" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
3-4 mm wide. Seeds elliptic, the two sides slightly bent, ca. 0.6 mm long.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="35968606280343D32274EB62708A6F03" pageId="0" pageNumber="19" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="9D336278EBFD625A525A9CBE334A7151" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B2B1B7B7F31BDCA22F212E3A224A8030" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">
The specific epithet refers to the flowers of this new species that are green throughout the flowering period, differing from those of all other known 
<taxonomicName id="4C5A60A833366BAF1F07FEE3613BAF6A" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Saxifragaceae" genus="Saxifraga" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Saxifraga subsp. sect." order="Saxifragales" pageId="0" pageNumber="19" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="section" section="Irregulares" species="kegangii" subSpecies="sect.">Saxifraga sect. Irregulares</taxonomicName>
species. The Chinese name is given as 
<normalizedToken id="32FC97E3392A0289CB06CEC3462AC09E" originalValue="“绿花虎耳草”">&quot;绿花虎耳草&quot;</normalizedToken>
(lǜ 
<normalizedToken id="A2A2AC5DE3402CDAC2CB096A86BA5EAB" originalValue="huā">hua</normalizedToken>
<normalizedToken id="02631F08F87300C1DC6D63160759C7E7" originalValue="hǔ">hǔ</normalizedToken>
<normalizedToken id="C1464CE9E61D09CB7E6B2F1D3895200A" originalValue="ěr">er</normalizedToken>
<normalizedToken id="AC6BB7739069F510F8C49B302589AD6D" originalValue="cǎo">cǎo</normalizedToken>
), referring to the greenish petals of the new species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="F82089246695478FBCA4664306E60A3A" pageId="0" pageNumber="19" type="phenology">
<paragraph id="BE08C8B378562A172AA995A5C4096229" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">Phenology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D3FC01D8F0A00CB8AA5206C2374DD3AD" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">
In a two year personal observation of this new species in its native range, Guangxi. Guilin City (Luo Dexuan, pers. comm.), 
<taxonomicName id="FCA44C4207828F175CFA8D91AC4A03F9" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Saxifragaceae" genus="S." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="S. viridiflora" order="Saxifragales" pageId="0" pageNumber="19" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="viridiflora">
<emphasis id="D382BF103429C2BAA21EE4150699A504" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">S. viridiflora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was flowering from April to July and fruiting from June to August.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="FBFF0FA85AC7BEE04FFDA396312A6A2B" pageId="0" pageNumber="19" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="23DA0D19FD59FF7C403C9FDE024EFA8E" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">Distribution and ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="60DD69C68273E29DBA6BD7BDA659C0EC" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">
The new species, 
<taxonomicName id="D978BB2021D8105EA1692541685F4EEF" authorityName="X. J. Zhang, T. Deng, J. T. Chen &amp; H. Sun" authorityYear="2021" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Saxifragaceae" genus="Saxifraga" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Saxifraga viridiflora" order="Saxifragales" pageId="0" pageNumber="19" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="viridiflora">
<emphasis id="3F64D212989EC89AE55FCD9155463D13" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">Saxifraga viridiflora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, is currently known only from Yongfu County, Guangxi Province, China. It was observed to grow on dry limestone under dense jungles at altitudes between 500 and 600 m.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
